properties.Name: DunBradstreetThreeYearsComparativeStatement
properties.Description: Up to three years of comparative summaries of a company's balance sheets, income statements and management estimates or projections appear in this statement.

Columns.Name: DunsNumber
Columns.Description: Dun & Bradstreet (D&B) provides a D-U-N-S Number, a unique nine digit identification number, for each physical location of your business.

Columns.Name: ReportPurchaseDate
Columns.Description: The purchase date of the report.

Columns.Name: FiscalConsolidatedDate
Columns.Description: The date of the fiscal consolidated statement.

Columns.Name: ReferenceCurrencyName
Columns.Description:
The name of the reference currency in which the statements are denominated.

Ex:
- USD

Columns.Name: CurrentAssetsAmount
Columns.Description:
Current assets are balance sheet accounts that represent the value of all assets that can be converted into cash within one year. 

Current assets may include cash and cash equivalents, accounts receivable, inventory, marketable securities, prepaid expenses and other liquid assets that can be readily converted to cash.

Columns.Name: CurrentLiabilitiesAmount
Columns.Description:
Current liabilities are the company's debts or obligations that are due within one year.

These are shown on the company's balance sheet and include short term debt, accounts payable, accrued liabilities and other debts.

Columns.Name: CurrentRatio
Columns.Description: The current ratio is a liquidity ratio that reflects a company's ability to pay short- term and long-term obligations, also known as the working cash flow ratio.

Columns.Name: WorkingCapitalAmount
Columns.Description:
Working capital is a measure of both the company's efficiency and its short-term financial health. 

Working capital is calculated as: Working Capital = Current Assets - Current Liabilities.

Columns.Name: OtherAssetsAmount
Columns.Description:
A company's other assets are those that do not include cash, securities, receivables, inventory and prepaid assets and can reasonably be convertible into cash within one business cycle - typically one fiscal year.

 Other current assets are listed on a firm's balance sheet, and are a component of a firm's total assets.

Columns.Name: WorthAmount
Columns.Description: Net worth  is the total assets minus total outside liabilities of an individual or a company.

Columns.Name: SalesAmount
Columns.Description: Corporate sales are the sales that a company makes to another company through its everyday transactions.

Columns.Name: LongTermLiabilitiesAmount
Columns.Description:
Long-term liabilities are liabilities with a future beneficial value over one year.

These include notes payable that mature longer than one year. 

Long-term liabilities are shown on the right wing of the balance-sheet representing the sources of funds, which are generally bounded in form of capital assets.

Columns.Name: NetProfitLossAmount
Columns.Description:
Net profit (aka net income or net earnings) is a measure of the profitability of a legal entity after accounting for all costs. 

It is the actual profit without inclusion of working expense in the calculation of gross profit.

Net loss (aka net operating loss) is the result that occurs when expenses exceed the income or total revenue produced for a given period of time.
